Project - FMST:Concrete Strength Prediction¶

Objective:¶

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file "concrete.csv". Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain a score above 85%.

Dataset Information¶

The data for this project is available in file https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learningdatabases/concrete/compressive/.

Attribute Information:¶

Given are the variable name, variable type, the measurement unit, and a brief description. The concrete compressive strength is the regression problem. The order of this listing corresponds to the order of numerals along the rows of the database.(see attribute table given in course notes)

Uni-variate analysis: insights¶

  1. Some of the prediction variables have zero values. However All variables are ingredients for concrete. Some of these can be zero depending upon the composition
  2. There are no null values in data set
  3. There are no missing values in dataset
  4. Statistical summary of the variables:
  • cement: slightly right-skewed because mean is slightly greater than the median. Also relatively high std
  • slag: right skewed, with minimum value of 0 and possible outliers. May need some further treatment
  • ash: right skewed with minimum value of 0 and possible outliers.
  • water: mean is slightly less than the median. Hence slightly left skewed
  • superplastic: slighly left skewed; minimum value of 0.
  • courseagg: slightly right skewed and possible outliers.
  • fineagg: left skewed and possible outliers
  • age: right skewed and the min and max values are 1 and 365 respectively. This is expected.
  • strength:well behaved and almost gaussian or normal bell-shaped distribution. min value is 2.33 and max value is 82.6

In [15]:
def label(data):
    if data["age"] <= 30:
        return "1"
    if data["age"] > 30 and data["age"] <= 60 :
        return "2"
    if data["age"] > 60 and data["age"] <= 90 :
        return "3"
    if data["age"] > 90 and data["age"] <= 120 :
        return "4"
    if data["age"] > 120 and data["age"] <= 150 :
        return "5"
    if data["age"] > 150 and data["age"] <= 180 :
        return "6"
    if data["age"] > 180 and data["age"] <= 210 :
        return "7"
    if data["age"] > 210 and data["age"] <= 240 :
        return "8"
    if data["age"] > 240 and data["age"] <= 270 :
        return "9"
    if data["age"] > 270 and data["age"] <= 300 :
        return "10"
    if data["age"] > 300 and data["age"] <= 330 :
        return "11"
    if data["age"] > 330 :
        return "12"
df["age_months"] = df.apply(lambda df:label(df) , axis=1)

In [17]:
df2 = df.copy(deep=True)
def lab(data2):
    if data2["strength"] <= 17:
        return "1"
    if data2["strength"] >17 and data2["strength"] <= 28 :
        return "2"
    if data2["strength"] >28 :
        return "3 "
    
df2["strength_category"] = df2.apply(lambda df2:lab(df2) ,axis =1)

Outliers. The strategy adopted was to compute the z-scores and remove the data points with z-scores > 3 . The threshold of 3 is a standard value used in such determination.¶
In [19]:
#calculate z-scores
from scipy import stats
#import scipy.stats as stats
z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(df2))
In [20]:
#narrow down data set to all columns wit z scores of less than 3
df2 = df2[(z_scores < 3).all(axis=1)]
print ("data frame with no outliers shape", df2.shape)
print ("data frame with no outliers describe", df2.describe)

Initial insights of the Bi-variate analysis¶

  • cement, superplasticizer and age have signficant positive correlation with strength.
  • cement has the relatively highest correlation with strength.
  • Most pairwise correlations between predictor variables are generally low.
  • fineagg and courseagg have the same -ve correlation value with strength so one of them may be dropped if desired.

3. Feature Engineering techniques(10 marks)¶

1. Identify opportunities (if any) to extract new features from existing features, drop a feature(if required) Hint: Feature Extraction, for example, consider a dataset with two features length and breadth. From this, we can extract a new feature Area which would be length * breadth.¶

  • From the correlation heatmap, and relevant literature, we explore the following new features:
  • product of ash and cement.
  • product of slag and cement
  • product of fineagg and water

ref:

  1. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0950061819320719
  2. https://www.scipedia.com/public/Silva_et_al_2020a
In [26]:
df2 = df.copy(deep=True)
def feature1(data2):
   return (data2["ash"]*data2["cement"])  
df2["ash_cement"] = df2.apply(lambda df2:feature1(df2) ,axis =1)
In [27]:
df2 = df.copy(deep=True)
def feature1(data2):
   return (data2["slag"]*data2["cement"])  
df2["slag_cement"] = df2.apply(lambda df2:feature1(df2) ,axis =1)
In [28]:
def feature2(data2):
   return (data2["fineagg"]*data2["water"])
    
df2["fineagg_water"] = df2.apply(lambda df2:feature2(df2) ,axis =1)

3. Decide on the complexity of the model, should it be a simple linear model in terms of parameters or would a quadratic or higher degree.¶

In this project we decided to use a multivariate polynomial regression model rather than the simpler linear regression model. The multivariate regression model uses the nth degree polynomials of the input variables to predict the output variables. In ths project we used a degree of 5.¶
In [32]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline

degree=5
polyreg=make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree),LinearRegression())
polyreg.fit(X,y)
Out[32]:
Pipeline(memory=None,
         steps=[('polynomialfeatures',

                 LinearRegression(copy_X=True, fit_intercept=True, n_jobs=None,
                                  normalize=False))],
         verbose=False)

def rmse(y_test,y_pred):
      return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,y_pred))

#Store the accuracy results for each model in a dataframe for final comparison
acc_LR = polyreg.score(X_test,y_test)
resultsDf = pd.DataFrame({'Method':['Polynomial Regression'], 'accuracy': acc_LR})
resultsDf = resultsDf[['Method', 'accuracy']]
resultsDf
Out[36]:
Method accuracy
0 Polynomial Regression 0.99908
In this project we also decided to explore the use of Kernalized Regression Methods. Kernalized regression methods utilize two mathematical concepts applied in tandem – a transformation of the predictor variables and the pairing of the new predictors with a regression method.¶
In [37]:
from sklearn.kernel_ridge import KernelRidge
kridge = KernelRidge(alpha=1.0)
kridge.fit(X, y)
Out[37]:
KernelRidge(alpha=1.0, coef0=1, degree=3, gamma=None, kernel='linear',
            kernel_params=None)
In [38]:
print(kridge.score(X_train,y_train))

0.6999706052045793
In [39]:
y_predict_kridge = kridge.predict(X_test)
acc_RF = kridge.score(X_test,y_test)
tempResultsDf = pd.DataFrame({'Method':['KernelRidge'], 'accuracy': acc_RF})
resultsDf = pd.concat([resultsDf, tempResultsDf])
resultsDf = resultsDf[['Method', 'accuracy']]
resultsDf
Out[39]:
Method accuracy
0 Polynomial Regression 0.999080
0 KernelRidge 0.711418

Creating the Model and Tuning It:¶

1. Algorithms that you think will be suitable for this project. Use Kfold Cross-Validation to¶

Evaluate model performance. Use appropriate metrics and make a DataFrame to compare models w.r.t their metrics. (at least 3 algorithms, one bagging and one boosting based algorithms have to be there). (15 marks)

For evaluating model performance we considered 4 algorithms in conjunction with Kfold cross-validation method. The algorithms considered are: (1)Support Vector Regressor (SVR), (2) Bagging Regressor, (3) Gradient Boosting Regressor , and (4)Random Forest Regressor¶

-

In [40]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.svm import SVR
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
scores = []
best_svr = SVR(kernel='rbf')
cv = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=42, shuffle=False)
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X):
    print("Train Index: ", train_index, "\n")
    print("Test Index: ", test_index)

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = X[train_index], X[test_index], y[train_index], y[test_index]
    best_svr.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores.append(best_svr.score(X_test, y_test))

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingRegressor
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
scores = []
best_bag = BaggingRegressor(base_estimator=SVR(),n_estimators=10, random_state=0).fit(X, y)
cv = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=42, shuffle=False)
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X):
    print("Train Index: ", train_index, "\n")
    print("Test Index: ", test_index)

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = X[train_index], X[test_index], y[train_index], y[test_index]
    best_bag.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores.append(best_bag.score(X_test, y_test))

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
scores = []
best_boost = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.1,max_depth=1, random_state=0, loss='ls').fit(X_train, y_train)
cv = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=42, shuffle=False)
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X):
    print("Train Index: ", train_index, "\n")
    print("Test Index: ", test_index)

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = X[train_index], X[test_index], y[train_index], y[test_index]
    best_boost.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores.append(best_boost.score(X_test, y_test))

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
scores = []
best_forest = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=8, random_state=0)
cv = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=42, shuffle=False)
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X):
    print("Train Index: ", train_index, "\n")
    print("Test Index: ", test_index)

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = X[train_index], X[test_index], y[train_index], y[test_index]
    best_forest.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores.append(best_forest.score(X_test, y_test))

2. Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit¶

Use Grid Search or Random Search on any of the two models used above. Make a DataFrame to compare models after hyperparameter tuning and their metrics as above. (15 marks)

In this project we considered 2 models to investigate if additional performance could be obtained by tuning. The 2 models considered were: (1) Gradient Boosting Regressor and (2) Bagging Regressor¶

In [50]:
param_grid = {'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.05, 0.02, 0.01],
'max_depth': [4, 6],
'min_samples_leaf': [3, 5, 9, 17],
}

est = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=100)
# this may take some minutes
gs_cv = GridSearchCV(est, param_grid, n_jobs=4).fit(X_train, y_train)

Results vs Business Problem¶

In this project, the business objective was to predict the concrete strength using the data available in file "concrete.csv".The prediction was to be achieved by applying feature engineering and model tuning to obtain a score above 85%. In this project we considered various models and showed how the application of feature engineering and tuning enabled significant improvement in score. Also scores in excess of 85% were obtained as a result of applying the feature engineering and tuning¶

For completeness we investigated the performance to be had with the use of the df2 dataframe constructed earlier¶
In [61]:
#separating dependent and independent variables
y = df2['strength']
X = df2.drop(columns = {'strength'})
In [61]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingRegressor
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
scores = []
best_bag = BaggingRegressor(base_estimator=SVR(),n_estimators=10, random_state=0).fit(X, y)
cv = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=42, shuffle=False)
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X):
    print("Train Index: ", train_index, "\n")
    print("Test Index: ", test_index)

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = X[train_index], X[test_index], y[train_index], y[test_index]
    best_bag.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores.append(best_bag.score(X_test, y_test))
